<DOC><DOCNO> AP880218-0054 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-88 0641EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Sebastian     02-18 0265</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Obit-Sebastian,0272</SECOND><HEAD>Shopkeeper Near Hearst Castle Served Likes of Winston Churchill</HEAD><DATELINE>TEMPLETON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   J.C. ``Pete'' Sebastian, who served thelikes of Winston Churchill and Cary Grant at his store outside thegates of Hearst's Castle in the 1930s and 1940s, has died at theage of 81.   Sebastian died Wednesday at Twin Cities Hospital of a heartattack, said his daughter, Mary Sebastian Hansen of Boca Raton, Fla.   In addition to running the store bearing his name, he served thetiny, rolling hills community of San Simeon as its postmaster,notary public and registrar of voters.   The general store, which included gas pumps, a coffee shop andpost office, is registered as a state historical monument, Ms.Hansen said.   Sebastian worked as a landscaper around San Francisco publisherWilliam Randolph Hearst's art-bedecked mansion in the 1920s. Now amuseum run by the state Department of Parks and Recreation, thesprawling home is one of the most popular tourist attractions inCalifornia.   Hearst, founder of the newspaper chain that carries his name andmodel for Orson Welles' classic movie ``Citizen Kane,'' oftenentertained celebrities and business and government notables at thehilltop mansion.   Churchill, Grant and playwright George Bernard Shaw were amongthe many prominent visitors to the store Sebastian took over fromhis father in 1933. He sold the shop in 1971 and retired, said BobBuddell, the store's present owner.   Sebastian told an interviewer in 1986 that he always consideredthe Hearsts neighbors, dating back to the pre-castle days when theystayed in the Hotel Bayview next to his family's store.</TEXT></DOC>